Kinetic energy works both ways. If being pursued a ship could fire a cloud of plain simple mines into its wake. The inertia of the oncoming vessel would make stopping or sufficiently changing course extremely difficult. The magnetic mines would clamp on and detonate. The only option would be to shoot them and there could be hundreds. Any area of space could be littered with mines but they would be rather easy to detect unless radar stealth technology were applied to them.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=whitestar60>whitestar60</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 121<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/10/03 9:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=173.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/leela1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Kinetic Weapons</span><hr size=1> Hmm, or better yet just fling some asteroids out the back....<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
